				\begin{document}$$\left( {\alpha {\text{hv}}} \right)^{{\text{n}}} {\text{ = A}}\left( {hv{-}{\text{ E}}_{{\text{g}}} } \right)$$\end{document}where α is the absorption coefficient obtained from UV–Vis spectra, hv is the photon's energy, A is a constant, Eg is the optical bandgap energy, and n depends on the nature of the transition in a semiconductor. As shown in Fig. 4b, straight lines are determined when (αhv)2 is plotted versus photon energy (hv), indicating that the absorption is due to a direct transition (n = 2) for both CuO59,60 and ZnO61,62. The bandgap energies of CuO and ZnO were found to be 1.45 eV and 3.14 eV, respectively. These values are in good agreement with those previously reported63–66.Figure 4
